==Demographics==
As of the census{{GR|2}} of 2000, there were 13,472 people, 4,374 households, and 1,237 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 2,307.0 people per square mile (890.7/km²). There were 4,748 housing units at an average density of 813.0 per square mile (313.9/km²). The racial makeup of the town was 93.98% [[White American|White]], 3.42% [[African American|Black or African American]], 0.30% Native American, 1.19% [[Asian American|Asian]], 0.05% [[Pacific Islander American|Pacific Islander]], 0.46% from [[Race and ethnicity in the United States Census#Race|other races]], and 0.60% from two or more races. 1.64% of the population were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] of any race.{{GR|2}}

There were 4,374 households out of which 9.6% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 21.0% were married couples living together, 5.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 71.7% were non-families. 38.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 7.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.97 and the average family size was 2.63.{{GR|2}}

The age distribution is 5.8% under 18, 65.9% from 18 to 24, 12.1% from 25 to 44, 9.1% from 45 to 64, and 7.1% who were 65 or older. The median age was 21 years. Both the overall age distribution and the median age are typical for communities dominated by a large university, here Appalachian State. For every 100 females there are 95.6 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.7 males.{{GR|2}}

The median household income is $20,541, and the median family income is $49,762. The [[per capita income]] is $12,256. 37.0% of the population and 9.2% of families were below the [[poverty line]].{{GR|2}}

Men had a median income of $28,060 versus $20,000 for women.  However, poverty statistics that are based on surveys of the entire population can be extremely misleading in communities dominated by students, such as Boone. Out of the total population, 6.3% of those under the age of 18 and 9.1% of those 65 and older were living below the poverty line.{{GR|2}}

==Media==
===Newspaper===
Boone is mainly served by three local newspapers:

* The [[Watauga Democrat]] is published on Wednesday, Friday and Sunday of each week,
* The [[Mountain Times]] (free weekly entertainment publication).
* The [[High Country Press]] (free weekly publication).

A smaller newspaper, The Appalachian, is Appalachian State University's campus newspaper published twice a week on Tuesdays and Thursdays. In addition to the locally printed papers, a monthly entertainment pamphlet named Kraut Creek Revival has limited circulation and is funded by a Denver, NC-based newspaper.

===Radio===
* [[WATA|WATA-AM]] 1450 AM is predominantly [[Talk radio|News Talk]].
* [[WZJS|WZJS-FM]] 100.7 FM is an [[Oldies]] radio station.
* [[WMMY|WMMY-FM]] 106.1 FM is a [[Country Music]] radio station.
* [[WECR-FM]] 102.3 FM is an [[Adult Contemporary]] radio station, mostly music, also University of North Carolina [[North Carolina Tar Heels|Tar Heels]] sports [[radio network|network]], and [[Carolina Panthers]] [[American football|football]].
* [[WECR (AM)|WECR-AM]] 1130 AM is primarily a [[Gospel music|Gospel Music]] and Local News station.
* [[WXIT|WXIT-AM]] 1200 AM is predominantly [[Conservative talk|Conservative Talk Radio]].
* [[WASU-FM|WASU]] 90.5 FM is a [[college radio]] station run from the Appalachian campus.
* [[WNCW]] 92.9 [[NPR|NPR Affiliate]] a noncommercial [[public radio station]] licensed to [[Isothermal Community College]].

==Law and government==

Boone operates under a [[mayor-council government]]. The city council consists of five members. The mayor presides over the council and casts a vote on issues only in the event of a tie.  As of October 2009, the City Council members are:  Loretta Clawson, Mayor;  Lynne Mason, Councilor, Mayor Pro-tempore; and Councilors: Rennie Brantz,  Andy Ball, Stephen Phillips, and  Jamie Leigh.&lt;ref name=&quot;List of government officials&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.townofboone.net/mayor/mayor.php |title=Town of Boone, NC: Mayor &amp; Town Council |publisher=Townofboone.net |date= |accessdate=2009-10-29}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Development==

Industrial, commercial, and residential development in the town of Boone is a controversial issue due to its location in the mountains of Appalachia. On October 16, 2009, the town council accepted the &quot;Boone 2030 Land Use Plan.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://boone2030.blogspot.com/ |title=Boone2030Blogspot |publisher=TownOfBoone |date= |accessdate=2010-10-31}}&lt;/ref&gt; While the document itself is not in any way actual law, it is used by the town council, board of adjustment, and other committees to guide decision making as to what types of development are appropriate.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.thelawrencegroup.com/boone2030/finalDocs/BooneReportFinalBook110609.pdf |title=Boone 2030 Land Use Plan PDF |publisher=Lawrence Group |accessdate=2010-10-31}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 2009, the [[North Carolina Department of Transportation]] began widening 1.1 miles of U.S. 421 (King Street) to a four to six-lane divided highway with a raised concrete median from U.S. 321 (Hardin Street) to east of N.C. 194 (Jefferson Road), including a new entrance and exit to the new Watauga High School, at a cost of $16.2 million.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ncdot.gov/projects/us421widening/ |title=NC DOT US421 Widening Project |publisher=NCDOT |accessdate=2010-10-31}}&lt;/ref&gt; The widening has displaced 25 businesses and 63 residences east of historic downtown King Street.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.wataugademocrat.com/2007/0312web/statedotpaves.php |title=statedotpaves |publisher=Wataugademocrat.com |date=2007-03-16 |accessdate=2009-08-09}}&lt;/ref&gt; The project is slated to be completed by December 31, 2011.

